    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-11-17T18:36:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-11-17T18:36:00-05:00" n="444"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d444">
                <head>444. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Mission to the United
                        Nations</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d444fn1">Source: National Archives, RG 59,
                        Central Files 1970–73, <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> 3 <gloss
                            target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss>. Confidential. Repeated to Algiers, Hong
                        Kong, and Taipei.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>New York</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-11-17T23:36:00+00:00">November 17, 1971,
                        2336Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4314. Subj: <gloss target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss> Statement in <gloss
                        target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss>.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BFK1">Bouayad</persName> (Algeria) approached <gloss
                            target="#t_MISOFF1">MISOFF</gloss> November 17 to query why <persName
                            corresp="#p_BGHW1">Bush</persName> had released statement to press re
                            <gloss target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss>’s statement in plenary November
                            15.<note n="2" xml:id="d444fn2">
                            <persName corresp="#p_BGHW1">Bush</persName>’s statement to the <gloss
                                target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> General Assembly is printed in Department
                            of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, December 20, 1971, pp.
                            715–716.</note>
                        <gloss target="#t_MISOFF1">MISOFF</gloss> replied that this was matter which
                        had been considered very carefully and that statement by <gloss
                            target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss> could not be left unanswered in view US
                        public opinion. <persName corresp="#p_BFK1">Bouayad</persName> said that it
                        fortunate US had not replied in <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss> to <gloss
                            target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss> statement since statement was generally
                        mild and merely restatement of <gloss target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss>
                        policy.</item>
                    <pb facs="0921" n="884" xml:id="pg_884"/>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_MISOFF1">MISOFF</gloss> acknowledged that this may be
                        case, but that it [not?] possible for US overlook such a statement in view
                        of lively interest by US public opinion in what <gloss target="#t_PRC1"
                            >PRC</gloss> does and says. <persName corresp="#p_BFK1"
                            >Bouayad</persName> said he understood US position and remarked that
                        Vice <gloss target="#t_FONMIN1">FonMin</gloss>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CKH1">Ch’iao Kuanhua</persName> had seen Algerian Perm
                        Rep Rahal November 12 to go over speech. According <persName
                            corresp="#p_BFK1">Bouayad</persName>, speech was far more abusive
                        against US and that Rahal had managed clean up speech to great extent. Only
                        point which had been over-emphasized perhaps was question of Palestinians on
                        which Algerians felt very strongly. He said this information should be
                        closely kept. When asked whether Algerians being front runners for <gloss
                            target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss>
                        <gloss target="#t_DEL1">del</gloss>, <persName corresp="#p_BFK1"
                            >Bouayad</persName> said no and that they speaking to <gloss
                            target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss> as equals. <persName corresp="#p_BFK1"
                            >Bouayad</persName> further pointed out that <gloss target="#t_PRC1"
                            >PRC</gloss>
                        <gloss target="#t_DEL1">del</gloss> is totally unfamiliar with procedures in
                            <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> and is still feeling its way around
                        and thus consulting with friendly delegations.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BGHW1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Bush</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
